# Business Insights

This document records the most relevant business insights discovered during the project.

Insights are continuously updated as new analyses are completed.

---

# Insight 001 — Customer Consolidation

## Finding

Several customers were registered multiple times in the operational system.

## Business Impact

Using the customer registration ID fragmented customer purchasing history and produced inaccurate rankings.

## Action

Customers were consolidated using standardized Customer Name and CPF/CNPJ.

---

# Insight 002 — Revenue and Profit Ranking

## Finding

After customer consolidation, the highest revenue customer was also identified as the highest profit customer.

## Business Impact

The initial analysis produced different conclusions because duplicate customer registrations split customer histories.

---

# Insight 003 — Customer Frequency

## Finding

Some customers purchase almost as frequently as the company's best customer but generate considerably lower profit.

## Business Impact

Purchase frequency alone is not a reliable indicator of customer value.

## Recommendation

Investigate:

* Product mix
* Discount policies
* Product margins
* Commercial strategy

---

# Insight 004 — Product Classification

## Finding

The original ERP product classification was too detailed for strategic analysis.

## Business Impact

Commercial analyses became difficult to interpret.

## Action

Original product subgroups were manually reorganized into broader Product Groups.

---

# Insight 005 — Data Quality

## Finding

Customer registration quality has a direct impact on analytical results.

## Business Impact

Incorrect customer identification may produce inaccurate:

* Revenue rankings
* Profit rankings
* Customer segmentation
* Inactivity analysis

## Recommendation

Customer registration quality should be continuously monitored.

---

# Lessons Learned

This project demonstrated that business understanding and data quality are fundamental before creating dashboards.

The most valuable insights were generated during data exploration and preparation rather than during data visualization.
